<Layout title="What Documents Do Brisbane Sellers Need Before Listing? | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Having your documents ready before you list can prevent delays, avoid frustrated buyers, and help you close faster. Here is the complete checklist for Brisbane property sellers." draft={draft}>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Documents Do Brisbane Sellers Need Before Listing?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Buyers and their solicitors will ask for these documents. Having them ready before you go to market prevents delays, builds buyer confidence, and helps you close faster.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most common reasons a Brisbane property sale slows down after a buyer goes under contract is that the seller's solicitor does not have the documents ready. The buyer's solicitor requests information, the seller's solicitor asks the seller, the seller tries to locate records that may be years old, and what should be a clean and efficient contract period turns into a frustrating delay that tests everyone's commitment to the deal. Avoiding that outcome starts before you list.</p>

      <p>Document preparation is not glamorous, but it is the kind of preparation that experienced sellers treat as a priority, because they have seen what happens when it gets left to the last minute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Documents to gather before listing</h2>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Certificate of title.</strong> Your solicitor can obtain this directly from the Titles Registry. It confirms ownership details, lot and plan information, any registered mortgages, and any recorded easements or encumbrances on the property. You do not need to locate the original paper title; your solicitor handles this, but they need to be engaged early enough to have it ready when required.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Council rates notice.</strong> The most recent council rates notice confirms your lot details, zoning, and the current rates amount. Buyers and solicitors use this to verify land details and assess holding costs. Keep a copy of the most recent notice where you can find it quickly.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Body corporate records (units and townhouses only).</strong> If you are selling a unit or townhouse, the buyer is entitled to a body corporate disclosure statement before they sign a contract. This is issued by the body corporate manager and typically takes several business days to prepare. Request it as soon as you decide to sell. Buyers who cannot get body corporate information quickly lose confidence and sometimes walk away from otherwise strong deals.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool safety certificate.</strong> If your property has a pool, you are required to provide either a current pool safety certificate or a Notice of No Pool Safety Certificate to the buyer before settlement. A current certificate is valid for two years. If yours has expired, organise a pool safety inspection before you list rather than after a buyer is under contract.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Smoke alarm compliance declaration.</strong> Queensland sellers must provide a smoke alarm compliance declaration at or before settlement. Ensure your smoke alarms are correctly installed and compliant before listing, and keep the documentation. Non-compliant smoke alarms can create last-minute issues that delay settlement or affect your contract terms.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building approvals for additions and alterations.</strong> If any structures have been added to the property since original construction, including decks, pergolas, carports, patios, garages, extensions, or enclosed areas, the relevant building approvals should be located and confirmed. Unapproved structures are a material defect and must be disclosed. If you are unsure whether a structure has approval, your solicitor or a town planning consultant can search council records. It is far better to identify this before listing than to have a buyer's solicitor raise it after a contract is signed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Easements and encumbrances.</strong> The title search will identify registered easements, but it is worth being aware of what these are before your agent starts marketing. Drainage easements, power line easements, and access easements all affect what buyers can build on the land. Knowing this in advance means your agent can address these points proactively in marketing materials rather than having buyers discover them mid-campaign and raise concerns.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenancy agreement (if applicable).</strong> If you are selling a tenanted property, the current signed tenancy agreement must be disclosed to the buyer and provided to their solicitor. Include the most recent condition report and any relevant correspondence about lease terms and timing.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pest barrier documentation.</strong> If a termite barrier has been installed at any point, locate the warranty paperwork and treatment records. Buyers, particularly in Brisbane where subterranean termites are a genuine risk, will ask whether a barrier is in place and whether it is current. Having this documentation ready demonstrates transparency and reduces the chance of a post-inspection renegotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The ATO clearance certificate</h2>
      <p>This is consistently the document that catches Brisbane sellers off guard. If your property is selling for $750,000 or more, the buyer is required to withhold 12.5% of the purchase price and remit it to the Australian Taxation Office unless you provide a valid ATO clearance certificate at or before settlement.</p>

      <p>The clearance certificate application is made through the ATO online. Processing typically takes several weeks, though it can be faster. The critical mistake sellers make is waiting until after a contract is signed to apply. If settlement is scheduled and your certificate has not arrived, the buyer withholds the funds and your net proceeds at settlement are significantly reduced. You recover the money eventually through your tax return, but it creates a cash flow problem that can affect your ability to proceed on a purchase simultaneously.</p>

      <p>Apply for the clearance certificate as soon as you decide to sell, not after you sign a contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What your solicitor prepares</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor prepares the contract of sale, title search, and Form 1 disclosure documents. They will also advise you on any disclosure obligations specific to your property. Engage your solicitor at the same time you appoint your agent, not after you receive an offer. A solicitor who has had several weeks to prepare is in a far stronger position than one who is scrambling to get documents ready in 48 hours because a buyer has made an offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why document readiness closes faster</h2>
      <p>Buyers who receive full information quickly are buyers who can make decisions quickly. A buyer who has the contract, the body corporate disclosure, the pool safety certificate, and the building approval records in front of them on day one of the contract period has no reason to delay. Uncertainty is what causes buyers to hesitate, seek extensions, or find reasons to reduce their offer. A seller who removes that uncertainty by being prepared gives the buyer confidence to proceed, and that confidence translates directly to faster unconditional dates and cleaner settlements.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Getting your property ready to sell?</strong> Daniel will walk you through exactly what to prepare before your campaign launches, including what your solicitor needs and when to start the ATO clearance process. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Get in touch.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>
